Judicial and praetorian stipulations correspond to some os the English contracts os record, e. g. recognisances : they are so-called contracts entered into by one party to a judicial or quasi-judicial pro- ceeding for the security or protection of the other at the order of the judge or magistrate. Mr. Hunter observes (Roman Law p. 290) that their real meaning is the weakness of the executive : ‘it is much easier to get a man to promise not to do some· particular thing, than, when it is done, to acknowledge it to be wrong, or to give compensation.' The division into judicial, praetorian, and common must have practically be- come unmeaning aster the abolition of the ordo iudiciorum privatorum and with it of the distinction between magistrate and iudex, ius and iudicium.
